  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me in Bari. Growing up with parents who both had advanced degrees, I was never taught to doubt my ability to succeed in any field, but I've noticed how deeply ingrained stereotypes about who belongs in science and technology can affect people. When I talk to my friends who work in tech or engineering, they often mention feeling anxious about performing well because they're reminded of the 'girls don't do math' or 'non-white people aren't cut out for coding' narratives. This isn't about individual failure—it's about systemic bias that makes people feel like they're being judged by a stereotype before they even get to show their skills. I think we absolutely need to address this. As someone who's self-employed and works in a service role, I've seen how important it is to create environments where everyone feels safe to contribute without fear of being labeled by a group they don't identify with. The solution isn't just about fixing the problem but about building awareness and changing the way we talk about success. For example, in my community, we could have workshops that focus on storytelling—how people from all backgrounds have contributed to STEM history, which helps dismantle the idea that only certain people belong in these fields. It's not about changing the system overnight, but it's about making sure that when someone steps into a STEM role, they don't have to worry about the stereotype that's been attached to their identity. I believe that by focusing on these small, consistent changes, we can create a more inclusive space where everyone feels they belong.",
